&lt;grin&gt;

Here's my real perspective.  When I bought my first boardgame, I was in
junior high school.  It was 1973 and the game was Avalon Hill's Luftwaffe.
And I didn't know ANY other gamers because that term had yet to be invented.
We were just teenagers in the basement, ignoring our parent's demands that
we go outside.  There were NO video games, no role-playing games, no
computer games and no miniature games that I had ever heard of.  And playing
board games was something that was considered vaguely aberant and juvenile -
something that our parent's figured we'd 'grow-out of'.

Here's two stories from today.

I lived in a four plex apartment in Portland, OR for nine years.  When I
first moved-in there was a young woman and her four or five year old son
living across the hall from me.  I befriended them - mostly because I'm a
very nice guy and not just because the mom was young, very sweet and very,
very hot.  After Xmas, her son knocked on my door to show me his toys - he
had a plastic fort and a 'real' catapult and some action figures.  So I
showed him and his Mom MY toys - boxes of 'em.  Julie gasped., said 'wait...
wait... wait' and ran back into her apartment.  And returned with a
photo-album that showed her two older brothers and their best friend (now
two cops and an investment banker) playing Fantasy battle, sea of blood and
Age of empires(?) in their basement.  I later met the two brothers and the
best friend and did work for all three of them.

Fast-forward a few years.  Same four-plex apartment and a young couple (he's
21 and she's 20) from California are moving-in downstairs.  Me, being my
usual helpful self, go downstairs, introduce myself.  I haul boxes and
provide beer to Jeremy and Tara.  One of the boxes I haul out of the Uhaul
is labeled 'Magik' and I causually ask Jer if he plays 'Magik' and his eyes
get wide.

&quot;Do... do you know Magik.'  I just nod.  And haul boxes.

Then my neighbor across the hall - Dan in his black 'Illuminati' t-shirt -
arrives from his shift at Geo-Hex (the now-defunct wargaming terrain
company).  I introduce Dan to our new neighbors and Jeremy is goggle-eyed.
He turns to the two of us and in a tone of utter disbelief asks us &quot;Are you
gamers?&quot;  We both nod and grin and he yells to his wife &quot;Tara!  They ARE
gamers.  We moved into an Apartment full of gamers!&quot;  And his shocked young
bride just rolled her eyes and backed-away.  Slowly.

My point is that gaming of ALL sorts - card games, miniatures, roleplaying,
video games, computer games and boardgames - is now mainstream.  It's not
considered childish or aberant any more.  And when these feral children you
describe grow-up to adult status, they will still have the gaming bug.  And
it is up to you to fully and completely exploit that weakness to your own
advantage.  I do it.  Routinely enough to make a living at it.

So chill.  Relax.  This ain't my first 'Wargaming is dead and life as we
know it is over!' scare.  Been there and done that.  And looted the
belongings to build my collection on the bones of those who did panic.

